  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 12.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "As touching our brother Apollos;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " rather, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "but as touching Apollos, the brother.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " It seems clear from this that the Corinthians, in their letter, had requested that this eloquent and favourite teacher might be sent to them. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "I greatly desired him to come unto you;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " rather, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "I",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "besought him much.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " There were at Corinth persons malignant enough to have suggested that Paul had refused their request; that he would not send Apollos to them out of jealousy of Apollos's superior oratory, and of the party which assumed his name. St. Paul anticipated this sneer. His nature was much too noble to feel the least jealousy. Both he and Apollos here show themselves in the purest light. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "His will;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "there was not will.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The word \"will\" most frequently means \"the will ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "of God,\"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " but if that had been the meaning here, the word would have had the article. It is used of human will in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 7:37",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ephesians 2:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Peter 1:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Here it means that Apollos had decided not to come at present, obviously because his name had been abused for purposes of party faction (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 3:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). This was all the more noble on his part because he seems to have been a special friend of Titus (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Titus 3:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). St. Paul would gladly have sent his two ablest and most energetic disciples to this distracted Church. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "When he shall have convenient time;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " rather, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "when a good opportunity offers itself to him.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Whether Apollos ever revisited Corinth or not we do not know. 1 Corinthians 16:12",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]